Comment Key: ClinicalExamComment
Comment Value: None

Overview Notes: Start Glucophage XR and recheck levels in 6 to 8 weeks. Also increase exercise to 5 times a week and consider seeing a dietitian to assist you with an appropriate diet. 
Comment Key: EyesightNote
Comment Value: None

Please start the glucophage and work on your diet and exercise and then follow up in 6 to 8 weeks. Thank you for taking the time to do your medical today and I look forward to seeing you again soon.

Clinical Recommendations: 
Men's Health Recommendations: 
Women's Health Recommendations: 
Overview Notes: Supplement with vitamin D3 and then recheck your levels in 3 months
Comment Key: MedicalHistoryNote
Comment Value: Praneel the most pressing issue identified today is that your fasting insulin levels remain high. Your blood sugar is still normal so you are not yet diabetic but if we don't address this now you may well progress to type 2 diabetes. Please start the glucophage and work on your diet and exercise and then follow up in 6 to 8 weeks. Thank you for taking the time to do your medical today and I look forward to seeing you again soon.
Special Investigation Notes: Insulin resistance and restrictive pattern on lung function (? due to sinuses)

Overview Notes: Start Glucophage XR and recheck levels in 6 to 8 weeks. Also increase exercise to 5 times a week and consider seeing a dietitian to assist you with an appropriate diet. 
Comment Key: SymptomScreeningNote
Comment Value: None
Special Investigation Notes: Insulin resistance and restrictive pattern on lung function (? due to sinuses)

Overview Notes: Try to eliminate sugar and refined carbohydrates. Recheck your levels in 6 to 8 weeks and book a follow up to discuss the results and the medication.

Women's Health Recommendations: 
Overview Notes: Start Glucophage XR and recheck levels in 6 to 8 weeks. Also increase exercise to 5 times a week and consider seeing a dietitian to assist you with an appropriate diet. 
Comment Key: VitaminsOrSupplements
Comment Value: Vitamin D
Special Investigation Notes: Insulin resistance and restrictive pattern on lung function (? due to sinuses)
